segments.text: The study is underway of what A&M should aspire to be.
What do you think the typical cross-section attitude was of the student body at that time regarding women, volunteer corps,
and racial integration.
If we'd had a student body referendum.
Well, I'll tell you, let me just go back and I probably can't talk on the racial issue because I don't think it was really even, I don't even remember it being considered or discussed.
I do know the two areas that was very, very touching my senior year in which seemed to be the most discussions around the dorm or the dining hall dealt with the change in the name of the school.
because I knew it was coming, and then letting young ladies come here.
And I think everybody publicly, any discussions was against it, but I think if you talk one-on-one or you had buddies talking, it wasn't such a bad idea.
But I can remember the dining hall one time when we had this meeting,
yay maroon yay white texas state fight fight fight you know because they thought we might be going to change our names to that i think that just about everybody
that I dealt with or anything I ever heard had the old saying, the old army's going to hell, you know.
And I don't know that I remember like I did when I worked in the Commandant's office or when I came back again and worked in the Commandant's office where you had all this
vocal just just drive you crazy as we'd say the redneck Aggies out there raising hell about you know alarm is changing that's good traditions are going to hell everything's everything's wrong and
And then I found out just how strong the former students are, a portion of the former students are.
And usually the one thing I observe later on, it's the person that complains about one thing, he's also going to be complaining about the next time something comes up.
But I think that I was probably...
not into the mainstream of what was going on because I worked intramural department for four years and I didn't, usually didn't read the battalion because, you know,

get always get back in time for CQ or this or that but but I do know that most everybody felt that that that we dealt with felt like it's terrible that they're going to let females that was the one big big problem and I remember when I graduated the chairman of the board of regents who had been
pretty well responsible, was giving out diplomas and there were two or three people saying, I hope that blankety blank doesn't give me my diploma.
Was that Sterling Evans?
No, no.
That was out of a gentleman out of Fort Worth, Mr. White Peterson.

And against him, as I mentioned earlier, you know, we can see again how wrong we were, you know, and thank goodness that there were people like him and General Rutter that did have the views of the future.
in terms of ethnicity and so forth, there was some ethnic variety in the student body when you were a student.
How did...
How were Hispanics?
Oh, I think there was a limited number of Hispanics here and they came in and they were accepted.
I mean, I think everybody and probably the main point about coming to Texas A&M was
You came in here and you were treated equally.
If you were a freshman, it didn't make any difference whether mommy or daddy were rich.
You were Fish Jones or Fish Smith.

But what was even more important with your class, which is very important, you earned your respect of your fellow classmates or you lost your respect of your fellow classmates by doing something dumb or stupid or not being bonded or part of the team.

and that's why again it changed so much when we had girls here because all of a sudden you don't have five guys going out to a movie together going out to eat together once in a while going to ball games together which did help in the old days bond the people together and but were you all even aware of the family income of your
of your outfit mates?
You had a general idea just based on discussions because you lived so close.
You knew if somebody was a little rich boy or whatever, but most of the time if the guy got out there and participated in intramurals, for an example, or
He was a sharp dresser, just as long as you were part of the effort.
If you were going to babble-bomb an upperclassman, it was an effort, and it meant that all the freshmen paid the price together because you knew it was going to come.
Or you did something which was considered good bull.
You knew you were going to get in trouble.
Who were, and I've got it phrased here, the notable campus personalities?
Who were they?
Well, I think at the time when I was here, I said back, and again, it'd be different for the different people.
You know, if you were in the singing cadets, definitely the director would have, you know, would have been the Bob Boone type of person, would have been very, very important in some people's lives.
I think overall, there was, I was not in engineering, but Dean Ranstall,
was later Basic Division, was a name that you go see.
If you had a problem, Mr.
Gay in the YMCA was another person that was really, really a first-class human being.
Everybody, of course, was scared of General Rutter, but General Rutter was respected.
You know, he was respected.
Did anybody ever play any, attempt to play any pranks on him?
Only on his dog.
Only on Ranger that would get painted up with every type of... Well, some of it would have slogans.
Sometimes somebody would be an artist and do a picture on the dog.
Just like Ranger would show up here, there, and everywhere.
Just like we had Tripod and then, of course, Reveille.
Nobody ever attended any Frank's present house.
I don't know if they did.
I never knew.
I lived in the other area where his house was my last three years, and I remember, of course, when the house burned down.
Were you here?
Mm-hmm.
Let's see.
Was I not?
I thought I was here.
What year did it burn?
I don't know.

maybe maybe maybe i had just come back and he was living over there i'd haskell i don't know i'll tell you what i do know uh my junior senior year uh lived in dorm 16 and and their youngest child who was quite a bit younger than bud being the oldest and then linda and jane and anne bobby

Bobby would come to my and my roommate's room every afternoon he adopted us and then the maid would come down there and yell for Bobby and I remember sitting in church one time when the rudders were going down to the front second pew where they always sit and Bobby yells mommy there's buck and I wanted to crawl under but I remember when the rudder's house uh
burned and they lived over on Lee Street and so I'd have to go back and look and see what year that was.
What about P.L.
Downs Jr.?

Pinky was just of course we all at that time I think most of us thought that something was wrong with him and he was just this funny old skinny guy that looked like he was going to collapse up there when he pulled his tie off to throw it at Yale practice but

It was quite a bit later before I think any of us ever found out what an outstanding individual he was and and his record and Oh, yes, everybody Lupo had a had a tremendous reputation because if there was a problem Especially if someone really got in problem you could go see Lupo and I think it was

John Adams told me that, and I know Red Duke worked for Lew and John Adams worked for him, but I think it was John that told me that he'd pick up the mail and lots of times there'd be just a check, somebody paying Lew many, many years later for borrowing money from him.
I heard Mr. Lupo say one time that he didn't think any Aggie ever had failed to pay you.
He didn't elaborate on having kept the books that accurate or anything.
For you, who were the key teachers, advisors,
as you think about it.
Right.
Oh, I think it's real.
I mentioned to you two or three times that I was involved in intramurals.
I was fortunate to work with Barney Welch and Mr. Penn Berthy, and then the last two years, my fourth and fifth year, Chuck McCandless came down here.
So with the intramural, that was very, very just outstanding.
What did those people teach you?
Well, I think they were just, all of them took an interest in you.

And you can't imagine when you're down here and first you're a country boy and you're treated and then all of a sudden somebody takes time to just want to know about you, how you're doing and all of this.
And then in the intramurals we had where you could be sophomore intramural manager and then junior and then senior and they had four seniors every year.
But if you had any problems, but the most important thing I remember about any of them, if you ever were in their office or anything, they'd talk to you.
And they didn't seem to be rushed.
And I know I mentioned Randall.
I was also in my undergraduate in rural sociology.
Well, I had Dr. Russell, Dr. Davis, Dr. Brown, Dr. Nelson.
These people were just outstanding human beings.
A lot of them had served in World War II, but a number of them were Aggies.
But they just took an interest in the students.
And if you were doing poorly in class, they'd talk to you about it.
How did Dan Russell describe him?
He was, a lot of people didn't give him credit, the students, for being as outstanding as an individual as he was.
You know, of course, he had been in Chicago in the Al Capone days and had gone to graduate school, but his
He was just involved in everything.
He got a lot of publicity, of course, from the project houses, but I think the thing I remember the most about him is helping students.
I know I had a thought that I might want to go into recreational work or scout work, and his brother-in-law was in charge of the City of Dallas Parks and Recreation Service, but just
the kind of individual you could go talk with.
And there were certain professors.
You had the outstanding professors in your arena, Ashcroft.
Dr. Ashcroft's probably my favorite professor of all times at A&M because
Although I would have a hard time saying Don Barker is another one.
Of course, I had Chuck McCandless for a couple, and just had so many in the second time around in educational psychology.
But I think Dr. Ashcroft was probably one of the most interesting professors.

Probably the worst professors were the chemistry with the standardized exam, because you could have a good professor, but then you'd have the exam when you go take it, and you'd wonder, where did this come from?
If you needed academic advice, where did you turn?
We had the Basic Division, which had a good reputation here.
It was kind of like General Studies, but it had some older men that worked there.
Were there some individuals you would call in the Basic Division?
Let's see, who would have, I'm trying to think who the names would be.
Austin Curley was there.
I had Dr. Curley in graduate school for a couple classes, and of course he's just a very outstanding human being.
What about R.C.
Potts?
I had, now you're talking about Dr. Potts in agriculture?

Yes, I got to meet Dr. Potts when I was a junior because I was going to drop out the end of my sophomore year and join the Marine Corps and then come back to school, and I quit going to class, and then my daddy decided I was coming back to school, and
Only time in my life he ever said anything to me, I guess.
And I came down, and Dr. Potts called me in and called me Mr. Henderson and said he was going to put me on probation.
And I said, Dr. Potts, I've got to see average.
He says, Mr. Henderson, I'm putting you on a no-cut probation for a full year.
And I didn't miss a class my junior year.
And when I came back here,
teach ROTC and as assistant commandant, I sat across the table from him one time at a meeting and I was just saying, I wonder if he remembered.
I know he remembered very well, but no.
I think that is shining, a shining example of
most of the professors here, wherever you were, they took an interest in the students.
C.K.
Esten, what an experience.
Was he a good teacher?
He was a good teacher, but, you know, if you went in there and you were kind of a country boy, you're about half scared of him and his language, and it's like a screaming Al Nelson, you know.
I mean, once you got by the first couple of weeks, you understood.
Yeah.
Those two, Nelson and Esten, would have trouble today in politically correct.
For more than language, too.
But I guess Don Barker would be, if I had to say one professor that I've had experience with that was...
the kind of man that would stay up here all night or come back up here and help you.
He was probably on the cutting edge of the computer industry at the time, and he helped more people with their dissertations and their thesis.
As you think back to your student days, did you ever feel you didn't get what you deserved in terms of grades and so forth?
we knew.
You pretty well got what you deserved.
I'll always remember in Ashcraft, Dr. Ashcraft's class, I had a 91.
It was the highest grade in the class, and I got a B.
And that's back when 92 was an A, and I always thought that was terrible.
And if I'd have just gotten on that last exam, who patented the barbed wire, I would have gotten an A.
No, I think to answer your question that...
Most of the time, I think the biggest problem, though, the biggest problem in my days, there was help, but you had to go look for it.

And I think Texas A&M now, especially the Corps of Cadets over here, they emphasize over and over and over, we've got all of these tools available, and we've got help available, and we've got counseling.
The average student seems to think they've got to go to Mr. Bill's the night before an exam or two nights before and pay all this money.
But I think a lot of it, if I had had the upperclassman or somebody when I started off, when I started having some problems, direct me instead of me having to go myself.
Because I was so wrapped up like most students, the core was more important than school.
Or it was to me.
And that's why I've always admired the students that come in here and they want to major in nuclear physics or something.
And they know they've got to start off and do well.
You never were in grade troubles, were you?
I know, but I never was really what you call really, really outstanding.
See, that's why I enjoyed being able to come back to graduate school.
And then I had completed five courses, I guess, on my Ph.D. and had all As, but then there was just three of us in the Commandant's office, and that's when I quit going to graduate school.
Now, when did you and your buddies study?
What was your typical study?
We were required freshman and sophomore year to study three hours a night.
Did you really do it?
Oh, yes.
Well, you sat at your desk, and let me tell you, it's hard to study.

It's hard to study when you've got the window open and it's 98 degrees, it's humid, or even if it's 88 degrees and humid, and you're sitting there and you and your roommate in those straight back chairs.
So it was hard to study.
The main thing is it's hard to stay awake.
How did you all keep the room cool?
Did you have a fan?
The best way to keep the room cool was that you were fortunate enough to have an upperclassman across the hall that left their window open.
We didn't have a fan freshman year, no.
But if you had that ventilation of just going straight through, you sometimes get a little air.
It just sometimes was miserable.
And I think everybody should go over to the Hart Hall today, where it's about $600 and something a semester, and see what it was like.
During your era, Korean War was over.
Were there any national or international events that were so striking that you remember where you were when you heard the news?
I think going back to your statement the Korean War was over with, we had a large number of NCOs, and most of those NCOs had been officers.
And that was always interesting because even though your ROTC class just met two or three times a week, those sergeants were very, very important.
And we were shocked to find out this was a major or lieutenant colonel or whatever.
But I think during my time,
I know the one event that stands out the most in my life was I was second lieutenant at Fort Bragg when Kennedy was assassinated, President Kennedy.
But I think if I go back and think about things that happened, I'd have a hard time really telling you.
I can't think of any.
That's why I think 9-1-1 was such a shock to this country.
We'd been a number of years without such.
that yes, you and I did watch the TV the night Desert Storm started.
And we got the commentary there from the hotel room, but I don't think it is.
It's not like our parents, when they had the many, many things from Roosevelt dying to victories in either theater or D-Day or
I'm getting ready to talk about traditions now.
Describe for you and your buddies a typical home football day or weekend.
What happened when and what all did you all do?
Well, the upperclassmen were usually pretty good about if you had a date, you were left alone.

Of course, your date would have to go down and be on the cement benches outside the dorm so everybody could look out the window at the girls, but the freshmen would usually, starting off your freshman year, unless
unless you had a blind date or a date with some sophomore or junior's girlfriend that was bringing one.
And that usually never happened because people usually stayed with their classes.
But midnight yell practice was always a big deal.
And you'd still have to be back at the dorm at a certain time in most of the outfits.
You know, they'd have it like 1 o'clock.
And then we'd have drill on Saturday mornings, which was football.
Was it held at?
And your day, it's held?
We were at the Grove, and then I guess it, and Bo could tell you on this, but I guess it was our junior, it seemed like our junior or senior year it went to Kyle Field.
But when it was at the Grove?
It was wild.
Oh, was it at 8 o'clock?
We had it earlier.
It was not the midnight yell.
But we also had two yell practices a week, you know, like you'd rush out a chow to get over there, and it was a...
black belt privilege to go to Yale practice, not the freshman, sophomore.
A large number of the juniors and seniors didn't go, and probably the best typical picture of that is what you see in the Bear Bryant movie when you see them in there and everybody just squeezed up.
And finally, because of safety, I would guess that was probably the reason they moved us out of the Grove.
But it was wild.
Of course, if we won the game, you know, you had the tradition of the yell practice.
We outscored the game, I should say, and we didn't in my five years here at college, we didn't have a 50-50 season.
So we hit the Myers and Fulberg era.
Now, as a fish, if you were to go down and try to grab the yell eaters and throw them in the pond, where did the date wait for you?

That was one of those deals in the stands you'd say, okay, you always had to walk in wounded, never outfit, and they'd gather up the dates, and then you'd meet somewhere, you know, and it was kind of like in the dorm.
Lots of times you'd gather up, because we'd march into the game, you'd gather up the gals and bring them to the stadium, you know, and you'd sit.
I often think how those girls must have thought, what they must have thought.
Yeah, did you?
Were you, did you have a steady date with her?
No, no, I never did.
I was one of those guys that probably didn't have a dozen dates in five years here, you know.
Did, if a guy had a first date with a young lady at a football game, did he still kiss her after?
Oh, yes, yes, yes.
And how did she, was she well aware of that?
Oh, yes, everybody was well aware of that, you know.
And would you practice that at Yale practice?
I can't remember.
I can't remember.
Do you remember any important football game pranks other than the turning the armadillos loose?
But the only thing I really, and it's terrible, that's why I have a problem talking to some of my classmates that can remember all this trivia.
I remember, not a prank, but I do remember going to Dallas
for the SMU game my junior year when it was so foggy in the night that Johnny Harton got killed, and the guy that had to wreck with him was set across from me in biology lab.
And so, and he was not injured very badly at all, but of course Johnny Harton was killed.

Pranks at football games, one of the things I always remember is when we were having the court trip, we'd always get briefs, start your freshman year, if they're throwing anything out from the tops of the buildings, you know, the back two ranks and the first rank breaks off and you're going, you know, and all of this.
And we were just gobbled up with the dumb tail, I guess, you know, we really thought.
There were just a lot of times we'd go to the games and we always remembered that the bulls were always around, so you were very careful if you did anything wrong.
It seemed like they were always in view of you during the day or something like that.
Among the great traditions, silver tabs.
Do you by chance remember anything about your first silver taps and the impression it made on you?
No.
numerous articles and I just Can remember going like we always went in it and I guess the one thing I remember then It was silent.

It was silent and the lights were out and I think of course nowadays It is still basically silent and you you you can see lights and you can hear people talking a little bit But it's still it's amazing.
I think probably the most interesting thing is I
I think we went even as seniors.
And now, we went to Silver Taps as a senior.
I mean, I think we all basically, of course, I think we all went.
And now, Silver Taps, if you go the first of the year or the first couple, it's usually crowded.
And then the numbers start dwelling.
And I know I've been a number of times myself since I've been back.
And usually, it's when you know someone or something like that is the reason you go.
But the students.

with the exception of the Corps or people that know something, I think, I don't think you have the turnout that you should, although I'm the first to tell you, and I've told you before, that I think the traditions are mainly kept and new ones come about because of the civilian girls, you know, here on this campus.
Did you ever hear of anybody even
thinking about a prank during the Silvertapes?
No.
I've never heard one.
That's kind of the sacred cow I've always thought.
The Silvertapes and Muster.
Of course, we had Muster.
Muster then, we had it and it was over with.
Now it's turned into such a big, big event, which is great.
When you first attended Muster, was it held out on the MFC?
MFC lawns, if I remember right, you know.
And do you have any feeling of what your first muster reaction was?
What did you think?
No, I don't.
I think it was just a, to be very honest with you, I think it was probably just another formation and another thing that we had to go to.
But I think somewhere along the first or second year, it became important to you, you know,
And we didn't have the large number of names called or things like you have now, too.
And now you see where Muster is really oriented towards the family of the deceased.
And they do so much for them.
And there's so much publicity.
But it's like everything else.
The student committees are so involved.
And it's a year-long program.
Okay, back on.
Bonfire.
How long did you and your buddies work on bonfire?
Well we, if I remember right, we had three day holiday here during the bonfire.
We went out and we went out to the cutting area.

now there were outfits that worked the stacking area and the band was always over there but we always went to the cutting area and it seemed like there was might have been one or two other Saturdays we worked but there were three days when we were out of school it was just a holiday
went out and worked on it, cut, and the logs were brought in, and that was just about it.

We might have one night when they'd call us out there to stack logs, but it was just really, a bonfire only lasted a very, very short time, and now it turned into, recent years, it turned into a full year.
And bonfire, in your era, was held on the drill field?
Duncan.
Oh, was it?
Oh, it was already over?
Okay.
And what kind of stack?
It was just the... One level.
And I think we may have started going into the second level by the time I graduated.
And...
It would always rain out there, and Duncan was muddy.
Did anybody ever get hurt that you remember?

It was a junior privilege to the cutting area to swing an axe and and we didn't have all of the machinery of course there was always a few bulldozers and it was seemed like my freshman sophomore year the two years you participated in it it it was just muddy as could be.
I know my junior year I was still involved and I've got some good pictures I've taken photography class we got good pictures of the
You could see at least 12 or 13 groups bringing logs out because you couldn't get a vehicle in, just carrying them.
But the worst thing was... Maybe a broken arm or something like that, but I don't remember any deaths or minor cuts.
I just don't remember us having any accidents.
And the worst behavior was somebody drinking a little?
I don't know that we ever had any in the outfit I was in.
But it was the night of the bonfire.
There was, of course, quite a few people getting drunk.
It seems like, if I can really remember right, my first two years bonfire, we went out there and watched it.
Then we went back to the Darm study.
It wasn't the production that it turned into once you start having young ladies here and young ladies involved in building.
From your era, what was the value
Oh, I think the real value
